I am. Understood in this new light, the Descartes Marion uncovers through close readings of works such as Passions of the Soul resists prominent criticisms leveled at him by twentieth-century figures like Husserl and Heidegger, and even anticipates the non-dualistic, phenomenological concepts of human being discussed today. This is a momentous book that no serious historian of philosophy will be able to ignore.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aMind and bodyxPhilosophy. 0aPhilosophy, Frenchy17th century. 4aDescartes. 4aSixth Meditation. 4abody. 4aflesh. 4aonto-theo-logy. 4apassive thought. 4asenses. 4aunion. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aGschwandtner, Christina M.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226192611423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226192611.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles